        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="head">
                    <marginalia_text> 
                        Eccè peritissima[e] acies duorum maximorum Imperatorum; non tam asperorum iam hostium, quàm flagrantium a[e]mulorum. Sic 
                        manus conseruêre acerrimi olim Duces: et exemplum placet animosis posteris.
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                Look: the most experienced battle arrays of the greatest commanders, not so much of rough enemies at this point, as of the ardent rivals. In 
                this way the shrewdest leaders once preserved their troops, the example also commends itself to bold successors.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text> 
                        Annibalis ordo.
                    </marginalia_text>
                <person name="Hannibal"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                Hannibal's formation.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="tail">
                    <marginalia_text> 
                        Tam ferox, sa[e]vumq[ue] pra[e]lium; et tam ingens, immanisq[ue] Victoria, quàm fuisse hanc necesse est: quàm nullis 
                        amplificata hyperbolis, aut passionibus aggrauata? À Gra[e]cis, et pla[e]risq[ue] alijs, quantò minora, atrociter, stupendeq[ue]
                        exaggerata? Romano Ingenio nihil novum, aut magnum, vel in ciuium virtute, vel in hostium strage. Vndè, vt ipsa virtus, sic 
                        stilus, pugna[e], quàm pompa[e] aptior; semper ferè acer, neruosus, et ad rem. Mirentur alij, et super coelum extollant 
                        mediocria: et strenue facere, et pressè dicere, Romanu[m] est. Ha[e]c apud ca[e]teras miracula; apud illos gesta pra[e]clarè: 
                        nec Heros apud suos Scipio, sed acer vir.
                    </marginalia_text>
                <person name="Scipio Africanus"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                Battle needs to be as fierce and ferocious and victory as heroic and vast, as this one was. So little amplified with exaggerations or 
                intensified with emotions! The Greeks and many others severely and stunningly exaggerated things of less importance so much! To the Roman 
                temperament there was nothing new or great in either valor of citizens, or the destruction of enemies. From which [follows] that the style is 
                just as the valor itself, suitable more for fighting than for decoration, and nearly always sharp, vigorous and to the point. Let others admire
                and exalt mediocre things to the skies. It is Roman both to act vigorously and speak concisely. Among the others these are remarkable qualities,
                but among them these are deeds admirably performed, and among his own people Scipio is not a hero, but an energetic man.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
